Remarks on Uniaxial Solutions in the Landau-de Gennes Theory

Apala Majumdar1 ¬†and Yiwei Wang2
1 Department of Mathematical Sciences, University of Bath, Bath BA2 7AY, UK.
2 School of Mathematical Sciences, Peking University, Beijing 100871, China.
Corresponding author. Email: A.Majumdar@bath.ac.uk
Abstract

We study uniaxial solutions of the Euler-Lagrange equations for a Landau-de Gennes free energy for nematic liquid crystals, with a fourth order bulk potential, with and without elastic anisotropy. In the elastic isotropic case, we show that (i) all uniaxial solutions of the Euler-Lagrange equations, with a director field of certain symmetry, necessarily have the radial-hedgehog structure modulo an orthogonal transformation, (ii) the‚Äúescape into third dimension‚Äù director cannot correspond to a purely uniaxial solution of the Landau-de Gennes Euler-Lagrange equations and we do not use artificial assumptions on the scalar order parameter and (iii) there are no non-trivial uniaxial solutions that have ùêûzsubscriptùêûùëß\mathbf{e}_{z} as an eigenvector. In the elastic anisotropic case, we prove that all uniaxial solutions of the corresponding Euler-Lagrange equations, with a certain symmetry, are strictly of the radial-hedgehog type, i.e. the elastic anisotropic case enforces the radial-hedgehog structure (or the degree +11+1-vortex structure) more strongly than the elastic isotropic case and the associated partial differential equations are technically far more difficult than in the elastic isotropic case.

1 Introduction

Nematic liquid crystals are classical examples of mesophases intermediate in physical character between conventional solids and liquids [dg, newtonmottram]. Nematics are often viewed as complex liquids with long-range orientational order or distinguished directions of preferred molecular alignment, referred to as directors in the literature. The orientational anisotropy of nematics makes them the working material of choice for a range of optical devices, notably they form the backbone of the multi-billion dollar liquid crystal display industry.

Continuum theories for nematics are well-established in the literature and we work within the powerful Landau-de Gennes (LdG) theory for nematic liquid crystals. The LdG theory describes the nematic phase by a macroscopic order parameter, the ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q}-tensor order parameter that describes the orientational anisotropy in terms of the preferred directions of alignment and ‚Äúscalar order parameters‚Äù that measure the degree of order about these directions. Mathematically, the ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q}-tensor is a symmetric, traceless 3√ó3333\times 3 matrix, with five degrees of freedom [dg, newtonmottram]. A nematic phase is said to be (i)¬†isotropic if ùêê=0ùêê0\mathbf{Q}=0, (ii)¬†uniaxial if ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q} has two degenerate non-zero eigenvalues with a single distinguished eigenvector and (iii)¬†biaxial if ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q} has three distinct eigenvalues. In particular, if ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q} is uniaxial, it can be written in the form

ùêê=s‚Äã(ùêß‚äóùêß‚àíùêà3),ùêêùë†tensor-productùêßùêßùêà3\mathbf{Q}=s\left(\mathbf{n}\otimes\mathbf{n}-\frac{\mathbf{I}}{3}\right), (1.1)

where ùêßùêß\mathbf{n} is the distinguished eigenvector with the non-degenerate eigenvalue, labelled as the ‚Äúuniaxial‚Äù director, sùë†s is a scalar order parameter that measures the degree of order about ùêßùêß\mathbf{n}, and ùêàùêà\mathbf{I} is the 3√ó3333\times 3 identity matrix [majumdarcpam2012]. The eigenvalues of the uniaxial ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q} are 2‚Äãs3,‚àís3,‚àís32ùë†3ùë†3ùë†3\frac{2s}{3},-\frac{s}{3},-\frac{s}{3} respectively and s=0ùë†0s=0 describes a locally isotropic point. The uniaxial ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q}-tensor only has three degrees of freedom and the mathematical analysis of uniaxial ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q}-tensors has strong analogies with Ginzburg-Landau theory, since we can treat uniaxial ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q}-tensors as ‚Ñù3‚Üí‚Ñù3‚Üísuperscript‚Ñù3superscript‚Ñù3\mathbb{R}^{3}\to\mathbb{R}^{3} maps [majumdarcpam2012].

As with most variational theories in materials science, the experimentally observed equilibria are modelled by either global or local minimizers of a LdG energy functional [dg, newtonmottram, amaz]. The LdG energy typically comprises an elastic energy and a bulk potential; the elastic energy penalizes spatial inhomogeneities and the bulk potential dictates the isotropic-nematic phase transition as a function of the temperature [newtonmottram, amaz]. There are several forms of the elastic energy; the Dirichlet energy is referred to as the ‚Äúisotropic‚Äù or ‚Äúone-constant‚Äù elastic energy and elastic energies with multiple elastic constants are labelled as ‚Äúanisotropic‚Äù in the sense that they have different energetic penalties for different characteristic deformations [gartlanddavis]. These equilibria are classical solutions of the associated Euler-Lagrange equations, which are a system of five elliptic, non-linear partial differential equations for reasonable choices of the elastic constants [gartlanddavis]. This paper focuses on necessary and sufficient conditions for the existence/non-existence of purely uniaxial solutions for the LdG Euler-Lagrange equations, with and without elastic anisotropy. This is a highly non-trivial analytic question; uniaxial ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q}-tensors only have three degrees of freedom and to date, there are few explicit examples of uniaxial solutions for this highly coupled system.

Our computations build on the results in [majumdarcpam2012] and [lamy2015uniaxial], although both papers focus on the elastic isotropic case. In the paper [majumdarcpam2012], the author derives the governing partial differential equations for the order parameter sùë†s and three-dimensional director field, ùêßùêß\mathbf{n} in (1.1) in the one-constant LdG case and studies uniaxial minimizers (if they exist) of the corresponding energy functional in a certain asymptotic limit. In [lamy2015uniaxial], the author addresses some general questions about the existence of uniaxial solutions for the one-constant LdG Euler-Lagrange equations. The author derives an ‚Äúextra equation‚Äù that needs to be satisfied by the director in ‚Äúnon-isotropic‚Äù regions; this equation heavily constrains uniaxial equilibria. The author further shows that if the uniaxial solution is invariant in a given direction, then the uniaxial director is necessarily constant in every connected component of the domain; we refer to such uniaxial solutions as ‚Äútrivial‚Äù uniaxial solutions. In [lamy2015uniaxial], the author proves that for the model problem of a spherical droplet with radial boundary conditions, the ‚Äúradial-hedgehog‚Äù solution is the unique uniaxial equilibrium for all temperatures, for a one-constant elastic energy density. The radial-hedgehog solution is analogous to the degree +11+1 vortex in the Ginzburg-Landau theory for superconductivity [brezisbethuelhelein]; the director field ùêßùêß\mathbf{n} is simply the radial unit-vector in three dimensions and the scalar order parameter, sùë†s, is a solution of a second-order nonlinear ordinary differential equation which vanishes at the origin (see (1.1)). It is not yet clear if there are other explicit uniaxial solutions of the Euler-Lagrange equations, even in the one-constant case, in three dimensions.

We re-visit the question of purely uniaxial solutions for the LdG Euler-Lagrange equations, in the elastic isotropic and anisotropic cases, without the restriction of special geometries or specific boundary conditions. Whilst we do not provide a definitive answer to the question - are there other non-trivial uniaxial solutions, apart from the well-known radial-hedgehog solution, for the fully three-dimensional (3D) Euler-Lagrange equations; we make progress by considering special cases and excluding the existence of other non-trivial uniaxial solutions for these special cases. Our main results can be summarized as follows. We firstly characterize the uniaxial solution in terms of the scalar order parameter, sùë†s, and two angular variables, fùëìf and gùëîg, that parameterize the uniaxial director. We derive the five governing partial differential equations for these three variables from the one-constant Euler-Lagrange equations and in particular, we recast the ‚Äúextra condition‚Äù in [lamy2015uniaxial] in terms of fùëìf and gùëîg. This is an interesting and useful computation that has not been previously reported in the literature. In terms of spherical polar coordinates, (r,œÜ,Œ∏)ùëüùúëùúÉ\left(r,\varphi,\theta\right) where rùëür is the radial distance in three dimensions, 0‚â§œÜ‚â§œÄ0ùúëùúã0\leq\varphi\leq\pi is the polar angle and 0‚â§Œ∏<2‚ÄãœÄ0ùúÉ2ùúã0\leq\theta<2\pi is the azimuthal angle, the radial-hedgehog solution corresponds to f=œÜùëìùúëf=\varphi and g=Œ∏ùëîùúÉg=\theta with sùë†s being a solution of a second-order ordinary differential equation. We prove that for a separable director field with f=f‚Äã(œÜ)ùëìùëìùúëf=f(\varphi) or g=g‚Äã(Œ∏)ùëîùëîùúÉg=g(\theta), all admissible uniaxial solutions must have f=¬±œÜùëìplus-or-minusùúëf=\pm\varphi, g=¬±Œ∏+Cùëîplus-or-minusùúÉùê∂g=\pm\theta+C for a real constant Cùê∂C and sùë†s is a solution of the ‚Äúradial-hedgehog‚Äù ordinary differential equation i.e. all uniaxial solutions with this symmetry are of the radial-hedgehog type, modulo an orthogonal transformation. Our method of proof is purely based on the governing partial differential equations for sùë†s, fùëìf and gùëîg. We also show that the ‚Äúescape in third dimension‚Äù director field cannot correspond to a uniaxial solution, since we cannot find a sùë†s compatible with this director. This has been previously reported in the literature under the assumption that sùë†s is independent of zùëßz [lamy2015uniaxial]; our proof again does not use such assumptions and only relies on the equations. Our last result in the elastic isotropic case concerns uniaxial solutions that have ùêûzsubscriptùêûùëß\mathbf{e}_{z}, the unit-vector in the zùëßz-direction, as an eigenvector; we use a basis representation of ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q}-tensors in terms of five scalar functions, two of which necessarily vanish when ùêûzsubscriptùêûùëß\mathbf{e}_{z} is a fixed eigenvector. We analyse the governing equations for the remaining three scalar functions to exclude the existence of non-trivial solutions of this type. Our result is not subsumed by results in [lamy2015uniaxial] where the author defines reduced problems in terms of invariance in one direction i.e.ùêØ‚ãÖ‚àáùêê=0‚ãÖùêØ‚àáùêê0\mathbf{v}\cdot\nabla\mathbf{Q}=0 for some unit-vector ùêØùêØ\mathbf{v} and our method of proof is different, which doesn‚Äôt rely on the ‚Äúextra equation‚Äù. Our last result focuses on an anisotropic elastic energy density in the LdG energy functional. The anisotropic term in the Euler-Lagrange equations is a non-trivial technical challenge. We apply the same techniques as in the elastic isotropic case, to compute the projections of these equations in three different spaces, and manipulate these projections to show that if s=s‚Äã(r)ùë†ùë†ùëüs=s(r) and if fùëìf and gùëîg are independent of rùëür, then we must necessarily have f=œÜùëìùúëf=\varphi, g=Œ∏ùëîùúÉg=\theta and sùë†s is a solution of an explicit second-order nonlinear ordinary differential equation. This is exactly the anisotropic ‚Äúradial-hedgehog‚Äù solution which has been reported in [mkaddemgartland1999] but ours is the first rigorous analysis of uniaxial equilibria in the anisotropic LdG case.

The paper is organized as follows. In Section¬†2, we introduce the basic mathematical preliminaries for the Landau-de Gennes theory. In Sections¬†3.1, 3.2, 3.3, we focus on the elastic isotropic case and in section¬†4, we study an anisotropic LdG elastic energy density. In Section¬†5, we present our conclusions and future perspectives.

3 Elastic Isotropic Case

5 Conclusions

We study uniaxial solutions for the Euler-Lagrange equations in the LdG framework, to some extent building on the results in [lamy2015uniaxial]. There is existing work on the uniaxial/biaxial character of LdG equilibria, they rely on energy comparison arguments and the fact that biaxiality is preferred at low temperatures, to the uniaxial phase, or that biaxiality arises from geometrical considerations. We purely use the structure of the Euler-Lagrange equations (as in [lamy2015uniaxial]) in this framework, and our results therefore apply to all critical points and not merely minimizers.

For a 3D problem, a uniaxial LdG ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q}-tensor has three degrees of freedom whereas a fully biaxial tensor has five degrees of freedom. By using spherical angles to represent the unit vector ùêß=(sin‚Å°f‚Äãcos‚Å°g,sin‚Å°f‚Äãsin‚Å°g,cos‚Å°f)ùêßùëìùëîùëìùëîùëì\mathbf{n}=(\sin f\cos g,\sin f\sin g,\cos f), we derive a system of partial differential equations for fùëìf, gùëîg and the scalar order parameter, sùë†s. We believe that this representation of uniaxial solutions will aid further work in this direction.

In the elastic isotropic case, under the assumption that f=f‚Äã(œÜ)ùëìùëìùúëf=f(\varphi) and g=g‚Äã(Œ∏)ùëîùëîùúÉg=g(\theta), we show that the only possible uniaxial solutions are f‚Äã(œÜ)=¬±œÜùëìùúëplus-or-minusùúëf(\varphi)=\pm\varphi, g‚Äã(Œ∏)=¬±Œ∏+CùëîùúÉplus-or-minusùúÉùê∂g(\theta)=\pm\theta+C, and s=s‚Äã(r)ùë†ùë†ùëüs=s(r) satisfies a second order ordinary differential equation. In other words, they are radial-hedgehog solutions modulo an orthogonal transformation. By using an orthonormal basis for the space of symmetric and traceless tensors, we can show that if ùêûzsubscriptùêûùëß\mathbf{e}_{z} is a eigenvector of ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q}, then ùêêùêê\mathbf{Q} necessarily has a constant eigenframe.

In the elastic anisotropic case, we can show the radial-hedgehog is the only possible uniaxial solution under the assumption that s=s‚Äã(r)ùë†ùë†ùëüs=s(r), f=f‚Äã(Œ∏,œÜ)ùëìùëìùúÉùúëf=f(\theta,\varphi) and g=g‚Äã(Œ∏,œÜ)ùëîùëîùúÉùúëg=g(\theta,\varphi). Although a complete description of 3D uniaxial solutions is still missing, we believe the radial-hedgehog is the only nontrivial uniaxial solution, at least in the elastic anisotropic case. Further, we consider model problems in this paper but these model problems are physically relevant, e.g. it is reasonable to expect that the uniaxial director is independent of rùëür for spherically symmetric geometries or that ùêûzsubscriptùêûùëß\mathbf{e}_{z} is a fixed eigenvector for severely confined systems, with ùêûzsubscriptùêûùëß\mathbf{e}_{z} normal to the bounding plates. The formulation of the uniaxial problem in terms of sùë†s, fùëìf and gùëîg will be useful for a completely general study of admissible uniaxial solutions of the LdG Euler-Lagrange equations without any constraints.

Pure uniaxiality appears to be a strong constraint but it is known that for several model situations, (see e.g. [amaz, henaomajumdarpisante2017]), minimizers are approximately uniaxial almost everywhere. Therefore, it would be interesting and highly instructive to construct ‚Äúexplicit‚Äù approximately uniaxial solutions. Our technical computations in the elastic isotropic and anisotropic case may aid such constructions and equally, similar techniques may help in classifying solutions (without the constraint of uniaxiality) of the LdG Euler-Lagrange equations.
